{
  "masechta": "Shabbat",
  "daf": 132,
  "amud": "a",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Eliezer's Position on Preparatory Actions for Mitzvot and the Dispute with the Rabbis",
      "display_title": "Machshirin & Mitzvot",
      "timestamp": "00:11",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer's ruling that even preparatory actions (machshirin) for mitzvot override Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Machshirin Override",
          "timestamp": "00:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Rabbis' disagreement with Rabbi Eliezer",
          "display_title": "Rabbis Disagree",
          "timestamp": "00:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Consensus that milah itself overrides Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Milah Consensus",
          "timestamp": "00:40"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Establishing the Source for Milah Overriding Shabbat: Halacha L'Moshe miSinai and Challenges to This View",
      "display_title": "Milah Source: Halacha",
      "timestamp": "01:04",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Ula and Rabbi Yitzchak cite halacha l'Moshe miSinai as the source for milah overriding Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Halacha L'Moshe",
          "timestamp": "01:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara challenges whether halacha l'Moshe miSinai can serve as a basis for a kal vachomer argument",
          "display_title": "Kal Vachomer Issue",
          "timestamp": "02:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Example: Rabbi Eliezer vs. Rabbi Akiva on whether a kal vachomer can be derived from a halacha",
          "display_title": "Bone & Blood Case",
          "timestamp": "03:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion that one cannot derive a kal vachomer from halacha l'Moshe miSinai",
          "display_title": "No Kal Vachomer",
          "timestamp": "05:19"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Alternative Derivations of Milah Overriding Shabbat: Gezeirah Shavah from Os and Bris",
      "display_title": "Gezeirah Shavah Os",
      "timestamp": "05:42",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Elazar's gezeirah shavah from os (sign): Shabbat is an os, milah is an os",
          "display_title": "Os Connection",
          "timestamp": "05:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's objection: if os connects milah and Shabbat, why not tefillin which is also os?",
          "display_title": "Tefillin Objection",
          "timestamp": "06:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Nachman bar Yitzchak's resolution: three terms must apply to both—os, bris, and l'dorosam (generations)",
          "display_title": "Three Terms Test",
          "timestamp": "09:03"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Yochanan's Derivation from Bayom (On That Day) and Challenges to Alternative Readings",
      "display_title": "Bayom Derivation",
      "timestamp": "10:59",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan: the word bayom teaches that milah is done even on Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Bayom Teaching",
          "timestamp": "10:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish's challenge: if bayom means even on Shabbat, what about korban offerings for impure persons?",
          "display_title": "Korban Challenge",
          "timestamp": "11:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman's response: bayom teaches daytime, not Shabbat override; the word is necessary despite other implications",
          "display_title": "Bayom Daytime",
          "timestamp": "12:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Acha bar Yaakov's alternative: shmini (eighth day) is emphasized to teach that milah is done even on Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Shmini Alternative",
          "timestamp": "15:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's preference for Rabbi Yochanan's bayom derivation over Rav Acha bar Yaakov's shmini approach",
          "display_title": "Bayom Preferred",
          "timestamp": "16:50"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaitic Source and Logical Arguments for Milah Overriding Shabbat and Tzara'at",
      "display_title": "Braita & Kal Vachomer",
      "timestamp": "16:59",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The braita: milah on the eighth day overrides Shabbat, even on Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Braita Milah",
          "timestamp": "16:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "The braita's reconciliation: the word bayom teaches that milah overrides Shabbat despite the death penalty for Shabbat violation",
          "display_title": "Braita Resolution",
          "timestamp": "17:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's question: what logical reasoning initially seemed to support bayom overriding Shabbat?",
          "display_title": "Rava's Question",
          "timestamp": "17:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "The kal vachomer argument: Shabbat is weighty, milah overrides it, so milah surely overrides tzara'at",
          "display_title": "Kal Vachomer Argument",
          "timestamp": "19:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rebuttal: one cannot be certain that Shabbat is weightier than tzara'at; tzara'at overrides avodah, avodah overrides Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Tzara'at Rebuttal",
          "timestamp": "22:41"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Milah Overriding Tzara'at: Derivation from the Word Besar and Counterarguments",
      "display_title": "Milah & Tzara'at",
      "timestamp": "30:19",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The teaching: milah overrides tzara'at whether or not it is the eighth day (in its season)",
          "display_title": "Milah Overrides Tzara'at",
          "timestamp": "30:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Derivation from besar (flesh): the braita uses the extra word besar to teach that milah is done even with tzara'at present",
          "display_title": "Besar Derivation",
          "timestamp": "31:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "The braita's logical structure: initially might think it's not done with tzara'at; bayom teaches it is done",
          "display_title": "Braita Logic",
          "timestamp": "31:07"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's analysis: what reasoning would initially suggest doing milah despite tzara'at?",
          "display_title": "Rava Analyzes",
          "timestamp": "32:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "The kal vachomer: Shabbat is weighty, milah overrides it, so milah should override tzara'at",
          "display_title": "Kal Vachomer Tzara'at",
          "timestamp": "32:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Counterargument: tzara'at may be weightier due to the tzara'at-avodah-Shabbat chain; need the word besar to resolve",
          "display_title": "Tzara'at Counterarg",
          "timestamp": "33:31"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Alternative Derivation via Aseh Doche Lo Taase and Its Limitations for Milah and Tzara'at",
      "display_title": "Aseh vs. Lo Taase",
      "timestamp": "34:46",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Alternate approach: milah is a positive mitzvah (aseh) that overrides the negative prohibition against cutting tzara'at",
          "display_title": "Aseh Principle",
          "timestamp": "34:46"
        },
        {
          "title": "Objection: tzara'at is also both a positive and negative obligation, so simple aseh-lo taase hierarchy fails",
          "display_title": "Objection to Aseh",
          "timestamp": "35:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "The braita's response: the word besar teaches that milah overrides tzara'at",
          "display_title": "Braita Resolves",
          "timestamp": "36:08"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Learning Milah Overriding Tzara'at from Common Denominator Across Eight-Day and Adult Circumcisions",
      "display_title": "Common Denominator",
      "timestamp": "36:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The word besar is used in the case of adult circumcision (eighth day) but what about intermediate cases (beinoni)?",
          "display_title": "Besar in Cases",
          "timestamp": "36:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye: learn from the common denominator between adult and eighth-day cases that all milah overrides tzara'at",
          "display_title": "Abaye's Method",
          "timestamp": "38:25"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Refutation of the Tzara'at-Avodah-Shabbat Chain: Direct Confrontation and Practical Inability",
      "display_title": "Tzara'at Not Weightier",
      "timestamp": "41:02",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Safra repeats the objection: if tzara'at trumps avodah and avodah trumps Shabbat, why shouldn't tzara'at be weightier?",
          "display_title": "Chain Objection",
          "timestamp": "41:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Answer: it is not that tzara'at is weighti­­er; even if you cut it off, the person remains impure and cannot perform avodah today",
          "display_title": "Impurity Reason",
          "timestamp": "41:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative answer from Rav Ashi: aseh overrides lo taase only when they directly confront each other at the moment of violation",
          "display_title": "Direct Confrontation",
          "timestamp": "44:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application: when cutting tzara'at does not simultaneously fulfill a mitzvah, the override does not apply",
          "display_title": "No Simultaneous Act",
          "timestamp": "45:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: tzara'at does not prove to be weightier than Shabbat; avodah would trump tzara'at in direct confrontation",
          "display_title": "No Weightier Status",
          "timestamp": "45:44"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaitic Dispute on Source of Milah Overriding Tzara'at",
      "display_title": "Tannaim Debate",
      "timestamp": "46:06",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yoshiya: derives from the word besar that milah overrides tzara'at even if tzara'at is present",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yoshiya",
          "timestamp": "46:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yonatan: argues from kal vachomer that eighth-day milah need not explicitly be taught to override tzara'at, since it overrides Shabbat",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yonatan",
          "timestamp": "46:16"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
